\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Advanced Linear Programming Homework 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I did two different versions of problem 5 because I thought the book may
 have made a typo.
 I labeled these problem 5 and problem 5'.
 Problem 5 is straight from the book, whereas problem 5' is a slight variation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

ZZ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=(x_{2}^{2}-x_{1})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all stationary points of this function.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}\text{ is a stationary point of }f & \iff\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\\
 & \iff2\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}-x_{2}^{2}\\
2x_{2}(x_{2}^{2}-x_{1})
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & \iff x_{1}=x_{2}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the set of all stationary points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{f}=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{1}-x_{2}^{2}=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From among the stationary points your found in part (a), identify those
 that are minima.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}_{f}$
\end_inset

 be the zero-set of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}_{f}=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}_{f}=\mathcal{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it follows that every stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a global minimizer with optimal objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all stationary points forms a curve in the plane drawn below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x_1 $, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $x_2 $, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-4,-2, 2, 4},ytick={-4,-2, 2, 4},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,thick,samples=100] ({x^2 },{x});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=above right:$ 
\backslash
boldsymbol{x}^{0}$] (x) at (axis cs:3,5.6) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, none of the stationary points are no 
\emph on
strict
\emph default
 local minimizers.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=(x_{2}-x_{1}^{2})^{2}+(1-x_{1})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all stationary points of this function.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}\text{ is a stationary point of }f & \iff\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\\
 & \iff2\begin{pmatrix}-2(x_{2}-x_{1}^{2})x_{1}-(1-x_{1})\\
x_{2}-x_{1}^{2}
\end{pmatrix}=0\\
 & \iff-2(x_{2}-x_{1}^{2})x_{1}-(1-x_{1})=0\text{ and }x_{2}-x_{1}^{2}=0\\
 & \iff-(1-x_{1})=0\text{ and }x_{2}-x_{1}^{2}=0\\
 & \iff x_{1}=1=x_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus there is only one stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{f}=\{\boldsymbol{a}\}$
\end_inset

 where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Classify the points found in part (a) according to whether they are strict
 minimizing points, minimizing points, maximizing points, or points that
 are neither minimizing or maximizing points.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a sum of squares, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is a global minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with optimal objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{Z}_{f} & \iff f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\\
 & \iff(x_{2}-x_{1}^{2})^{2}+(1-x_{1})^{2}=0\\
 & \iff x_{2}-x_{1}^{2}=0\text{ and }1-x_{1}=0\\
 & \iff x_{1}=1=x_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}_{f}=\{\boldsymbol{a}\}=\mathcal{S}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\neq\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})>0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
strict 
\emph default
global minimizer (and the only one at that).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=ax_{1}^{2}e^{x_{2}}+x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For what values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}=[0,0,0]^{\top}$
\end_inset

 a stationary point? 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}_{0}\text{ is a stationary point of }f & \iff\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x}_{0})=0\\
 & \iff\begin{pmatrix}2ax_{1}e^{x_{2}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}}\\
ax_{1}^{2}e^{x_{2}}+2x_{2}e^{x_{3}}\\
x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}+2x_{3}e^{x_{1}}
\end{pmatrix}\Bigg|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}}=0\\
 & \iff0=0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a stationary point.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Classify the points as a strict minimum, minimum, maximum, or strict maximum
 for the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 found in part (a).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We break this into three cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1: 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{H}_{f}(\boldsymbol{x}_{0}) & =\begin{pmatrix}2ae^{x_{2}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}} & 2ax_{1}e^{x_{2}} & 2x_{3}e^{x_{1}}\\
2ax_{1}e^{x_{2}} & ax_{1}^{2}e^{x_{2}}+2e^{x_{3}} & 2x_{2}e^{x_{3}}\\
2x_{3}e^{x_{1}} & 2x_{2}e^{x_{3}} & 2e^{x_{1}}+x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}
\end{pmatrix}\Bigg|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}2a & 0 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 2
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, the Hessian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a strict minimizing point (with objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x}_{0})=0$
\end_inset

).
 Next, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{Z}_{f} & \iff f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\\
 & \iff ax_{1}^{2}e^{x_{2}}+x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}}=0\\
 & \iff(\sqrt{a}x_{1}e^{x_{2}/2})^{2}+(x_{2}e^{x_{3}/2})^{2}+(x_{3}e^{x_{1}/2})^{2}=0\\
 & \iff\sqrt{a}x_{1}e^{x_{2}/2}=0\text{ and }x_{2}e^{x_{3}/2}=0\text{ and }x_{3}e^{x_{1}/2}=0\\
 & \iff x_{1}=x_{2}=x_{3}=0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{a}>0$
\end_inset

 and where we used the fact that the exponential function is strictly positive
 on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a strict global minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (and in fact the only one).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 2: 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x}_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a global minimizer with optimal objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x}_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Next, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{Z}_{f} & \iff f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\\
 & \iff x_{2}^{2}e^{x_{3}}+x_{3}^{2}e^{x_{1}}=0\\
 & \iff(x_{2}e^{x_{3}/2})^{2}+(x_{3}e^{x_{1}/2})^{2}=0\\
 & \iff x_{2}e^{x_{3}/2}=0\text{ and }x_{3}e^{x_{1}/2}=0\\
 & \iff x_{2}=0=x_{3},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that the exponential function is strictly positive
 on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}_{f}=\{(t,0,0)\mid t\in\mathbb{R}\}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, the value of the objective function neither 
\emph on
increases 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
decreases
\series bold
 
\series default
\emph default
if we move along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

-axis (in either direction) away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 (we could have also determined this by looking at the Hessian and seeing
 that one of its eigenvalues is zero with 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0,0)^{\top}$
\end_inset

 being a corresponding eigenvector).
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a strict global minimizer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 3: 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a<0$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{t}=(t,0,0)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{x}}_{t}=(0,t,0)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{x}_{t})=at^{2}<0\quad\text{and}\quad f(\widehat{\boldsymbol{x}}_{t})=t^{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, the value of the objective function 
\emph on
decreases
\series bold
 
\series default
\emph default
if we move along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

-axis (in either direction) away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the value of the objective function 
\emph on
increases
\series bold
 
\series default
\emph default
if we move along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

-axis (in either direction) away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 (we could have also determined this by looking at the Hessian and seeing
 that it has mixed positive and negative eigenvalues).
 It follow that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a saddle point.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=x_{1}-x_{2}+x_{3}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the following NLP
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad f(\boldsymbol{x})\\
\text{subject to} & \quad g(\boldsymbol{x})\leq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 4.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write the KKT FONC to this NLP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A KKT point for this NLP is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\mu)\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Stationary}\nonumber \\
g(\boldsymbol{x}) & \leq0 &  & \text{Primal Feasibility}\label{eq:KKT1}\\
\mu & \geq0 &  & \text{Dual Feasibility}\nonumber \\
\mu g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Complementary Slackness}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all KKT points for this NLP.
 The KKT FONC says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a local minimizer and the NLP satisfies some regularity conditions,
 then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 The regularity condition that we will use is the LICQ condition, which
 says the gradients of the active inequality constraints and the gradients
 of the equality constraints are linearly independent at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

.
 What this means in this case is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{a})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})=\begin{pmatrix}1\\
-1\\
1
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{1}\\
2x_{2}\\
2x_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:KKT1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1+2\mu x_{1} & =0\\
-1+2\mu x_{2} & =0\\
1+2\mu x_{3} & =0\\
x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1 & \leq0\\
\mu & \geq0\\
\mu(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We also note that the regulartiy condition is always satisfied since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0)=-1\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 4.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)$
\end_inset

 to the KKT FONC for this NLP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\mu)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 From the Stationary equations, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=0 & \iff\begin{pmatrix}1+2\mu x_{1}\\
-1+2\mu x_{2}\\
1+2\mu x_{3}
\end{pmatrix}=0\\
 & \iff\boldsymbol{x}=\frac{1}{2\mu}\begin{pmatrix}-1\\
1\\
-1
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by the Complementary Slackness equation, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =g(\boldsymbol{x})\\
 & =x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1\\
 & =\frac{1}{4\mu^{2}}+\frac{1}{4\mu^{2}}+\frac{1}{4\mu^{2}}-1\\
 & =\frac{3}{4\mu^{2}}-1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Equivalently, this says 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\sqrt{3}/2$
\end_inset

 (where this is the positive square root since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq0$
\end_inset

 by the Dual Feasibility property).
 From this it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{3}=-\sqrt{3}/3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=\sqrt{3}/3$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 consists of one point, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=\{(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha)\}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha)=(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\alpha)=\left(\frac{-\sqrt{3}}{3},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3},\frac{-\sqrt{3}}{3},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 4.c
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all optimal solutions to this NLP.
 Give their properties (choose from local, global, strict local, unique
 global).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From parts a and b, we see that the only possible local minimizer is the
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}(-1,1,-1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is affine and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is convex (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{g}(\boldsymbol{x})=2\cdot\mathrm{I}_{3}$
\end_inset

), the KKT SOSC are satisfied, which tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a local minimizer for this NLP.
 Furthermore, note that the feasible region 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\leq1\}:=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\mid\|\boldsymbol{x}\|\leq1\}$
\end_inset

 is compact, and combining this with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a global minimizer in the feasible region (which must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 since it's the only possible one).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=x_{1}^{2}-x_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=-(x_{1}-2)^{2}-x_{2}^{2}+4$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the following NLP:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad f(\boldsymbol{x})\\
\text{subject to} & \quad g(\boldsymbol{x})\leq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 5.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write the KKT FONC to this NLP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A KKT point for this NLP is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\mu)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Stationary}\nonumber \\
g(\boldsymbol{x}) & \leq0 &  & \text{Primal Feasibility}\label{eq:KKT1-1}\\
\mu & \geq0 &  & \text{Dual Feasibility}\nonumber \\
\mu g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Complementary Slackness}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all KKT points for this NLP.
 The KKT FONC says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{1},a_{2})\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a local minimizer and the NLP satisfies some regularity conditions,
 then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 The regularity condition that we will use is the LICQ condition, which
 says the gradients of the active inequality constraints and the gradients
 of the equality constraints are linearly independent at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

.
 What this means in this case is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{a})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})=2\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}\\
-x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=2\begin{pmatrix}-(x_{1}-2)\\
-x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:KKT1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{1}-\mu(x_{1}-2) & =0\\
-x_{2}-\mu x_{2} & =0\\
4-(x_{1}-2)^{2}-x_{2}^{2} & \leq0\\
\mu & \geq0\\
\mu(4-(x_{1}-2)^{2}-x_{2}^{2}) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We also note that the regulartiy condition is always satisfied since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(2,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(2,0)=4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 5.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)$
\end_inset

 to the KKT FONC for this NLP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},\mu)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 From the Stationary property, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=0 & \iff\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}-\mu(x_{1}-2)\\
-x_{2}-\mu x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=0\\
 & \iff\begin{pmatrix}(1-\mu)x_{1}+2\mu\\
(-1-\mu)x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=0\\
 & \iff x_{1}=\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}\text{ and }x_{2}(\mu+1)=0\\
 & \iff x_{1}=\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}\text{ and }x_{2}=0 & \text{since }\mu\geq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the Complementary Slackness property, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0=x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\neq0$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(\boldsymbol{x})=0 & \implies\left(\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}-2\right)^{2}=4\\
 & \iff\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}-2=2\text{ or }\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}-2=-2\\
 & \iff\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}=4\text{ or }\frac{2\mu}{\mu-1}=0\\
 & \iff\frac{\mu}{\mu-1}=2 & \text{since }\mu\neq0\\
 & \iff\mu=2.\\
 & \implies x_{1}=4.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have found all KKT points, they are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=\{(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha),(\boldsymbol{b},\beta)\}$
\end_inset

, where we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha) & =(a_{1},a_{2},\alpha)=(0,0,0)\\
(\boldsymbol{b},\beta) & =(b_{1},b_{2},\beta)=(4,0,2).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 5.c
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all optimal solutions to this NLP.
 Give their properties (choose from local, global, strict local, unique
 global).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We solve this problem geometrically:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

