end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The feasible region (that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\leq0\}:=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid g(\boldsymbol{x})\leq0$
\end_inset

) is everywhere 
\emph on
inside 
\emph default
the region shaded in red (including the thick red circle).
 The blue dashed lines above are level sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f=c\}:=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=c\}$
\end_inset

 for various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (namely for 
\begin_inset Formula $c=-2,-1,0,1,4,9,16$
\end_inset

).
 We also plotted the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 b ecause we know that these are the only possible points that can be local
 minimizers.
 Note that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(\boldsymbol{c})=2(1,-\sqrt{3})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 is normal to the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g=0\}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the level set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f=16\}$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g=0\}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 is a strict local minimizer with optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{d})=16$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 is a strict local minimizer with optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{c})=16$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 are global minimizers since the feasible region is compact and since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must have a global minimizer somewhere in the feasible region).
 Finally, by the same argument as above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is a saddle point hence not an optimal solution.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this problem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=-(x_{1}-1)^{3}+x_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 consider the following NLP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad f(\boldsymbol{x})\\
\text{subject to} & \quad g(\boldsymbol{x})\leq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 6.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Solve the problem graphically.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We solve this graphically as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x_1 $, 
\end_layout

