\begin_layout Standard
The feasible region 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\leq0\}$
\end_inset

 is everything to the 
\emph on
right 
\emph default
of the red curve drawn above.
 The blue dashed lines above are level sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f=c\}$
\end_inset

 for various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (namely for 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1,4,9$
\end_inset

).
 We also plotted the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}:=(1,0)$
\end_inset

 which is clearly the unique global minimizer with the objective optimal
 value being 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{a})=1$
\end_inset

.
 To verify that this is the global minimizer, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset

 is in the feasible region.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{2}\leq0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\neq\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\boldsymbol{x}) & =x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}\\
 & >1+x_{2}^{2}\\
 & \geq1\\
 & =f(\boldsymbol{a}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is the unique global minimizer for this NLP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 6.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write down the KKT conditions for this problem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A KKT point for this NLP is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},\mu)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Stationary}\nonumber \\
g(\boldsymbol{x}) & \leq0 &  & \text{Primal Feasibility}\label{eq:KKT1-1-1-1}\\
\mu & \geq0 &  & \text{Dual Feasibility}\nonumber \\
\mu g(\boldsymbol{x}) & =0 &  & \text{Complementary Slackness}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all KKT points for this NLP.
 The KKT FONC says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a local minimizer and the NLP satisfies some regularity conditions,
 then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{*}\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x}^{*},\mu^{*})\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 The regularity condition that we will use is the LICQ condition, which
 says the gradients of the active inequality constraints and the gradients
 of the equality constraints are linearly independent at 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 What this means in this case is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})=2\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=\begin{pmatrix}-3(x_{1}-1)^{2}\\
2x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:KKT1-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2} & =0\\
x_{2}+\mu x_{2} & =0\\
x_{2}^{2}-(x_{1}-1)^{3} & \leq0\\
\mu & \geq0\\
\mu(x_{2}^{2}-(x_{1}-1)^{3}) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that we've already found the optimal solution, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(1,0)$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy the regularity condition since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g(\boldsymbol{a})=0=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

, so it need not be the case that there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{a},\alpha)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 (in fact, the next problem will show that it's not the case).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 6.c
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Do the KKT conditions yield the optimal solution? Explain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 No.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{x},\mu)=(x_{1},x_{2},\mu)\in\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 From the Stationary equations, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla f(\boldsymbol{x})+\mu\nabla g(\boldsymbol{x})=0 & \iff\begin{pmatrix}2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2}\\
(\mu+1)x_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=0\\
 & \iff2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2}=0\text{ and }(\mu+1)x_{2}=0\\
 & \iff2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2}=0\text{ and }x_{2}=0 & \text{since }\mu\geq0\\
 & \iff2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2}=0\text{ and }x_{2}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

, then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume for contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the Complementary Slackness equation implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(\boldsymbol{x})=0 & \implies(x_{1}-1)^{3}=x_{2}^{2}\\
 & \implies(x_{1}-1)^{3}=0\\
 & \implies x_{1}=1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, then plugging this into the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2x_{1}-3\mu(x_{1}-1)^{2}=0
\]

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $2=0$
\end_inset

, an obvious contradiction.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, so the only KKT point is 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0,0)$
\end_inset

, which is not the optimal solution.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
